ce:section.ce:para:
EPR is usually used to detect the paramagnetic centers, regardless inner or outer portion of the materials, ranging from transition metal ions to defects and radicals which are singly anionic ionized [31]. In order to explore the effect of concentration of VOs on the performance of SnO2, EPR analysis was carried out (Fig. 5
                     ). As for SnO2, the singly ionized oxygen vacancy (VO

                     ) is deemed to be the main paramagnetic species. Hence, we selected four typical samples to investigate the existence of VOs as well as the effect of the relative contents of VOs on photoresponse. Inset photograph shows corresponding colors of samples. Generally speaking, supernal relative intensity symbolizes more VOs in the case of other factors remain unchanged. The deeper color of GQDs@SnO2 composites shown in the inset photograph proves the existence of more VOs compared with pure stannic oxide. It shows no distinct signal of ionized oxygen vacancy mainly because of relatively low content compared to GQDs@SnO2-VOs nanocompounds. The obvious signals corresponding to g=2.002±0.0004 in GQDs@SnO2-VOs-4 and GQDs@SnO2-VOs-5 indicate the more existence of VOs. What is more, the black sample of GQDs@SnO2-VOs-4 possesses prominent signal intensity of all, which results in its distinguished response to visible-light shown in Fig. 4. On one hand, VOs extend the photoresponse of SnO2 from UV to visible light region, which elevates visible-light photocatalytic activity; on the other, they also provide vital reactive agents for many adsorbents and reduce the recombination rates of electron-hole pairs [32]. Thereby, GQDs@SnO2-VOs-4 reveals the best photocatalytic performance with the dominant effect of VOs.
